column168: A van trailer picked up a shipment of drums and returned to the intended waste disposal facility.  The driver checked the load prior to releasing it to the waste disposal facility and noticed a small amount of liquid had leaked out of a drum and onto the floor of the trailer.  He immediately notifed plant personnel who donned the appropriate PPE and overpacked the drum into a suitable salvage drum.  The spill on the trailer floor was contained with aborbent pads.  No material had leaked onto the ground.  The drum and the pads were then unloaded by the intended waste disposal facility where they were processed for disposal.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transport, no evidnce of leaking was observed.  In order to prevent a recurrence, both the shipper and the driver were advised to take all appropriate steps to inspect each container beofre offering or accepting for transportaiton.  In addition, they were advised that all reasonable steps are to be taken such as transferring the contents into a suitbale container or placing a suspect container into a salvage container should a container with questionable structural integrity be found.

column168: Driver was unloading product using his pump and product hoses. driver had 60 feet of 2 inch discharge to the customers receiving line. driver had to push product up  two stories to the top of customers tank.  After to cargo tank went empty the driver ran 10 gallons of solvent through his pump and into the storage tank. Driver than decided to clear the remainder of material from his discharge hose with compressed air. Driver closed the cargo tank valves and disconnected his suction hoses from pump and tank. Driver than connected air hose to a fitting on the discharge side of the pump. He opened air valve immediatlly air and residual material sprayed out of the suction side of the pump. Driver shut air valve. spill was contained and cleaned up. by driver. Driver had failed to cap the inlet side of the pump after removing the product hose.
column169: Driver made several mistakes. he had someone helping him which was a distraction he lost focus. driver should have stopped and rechecked his connectiond before he opened his air valve. He could have cleared his lines without removing the suction lines. he didnot need to use air to clear his lines. he is only responsible for clearing his hoses and he could have drained them easily to a bucket.   driver will be discliplined to company policy which includes some level of   retraining.

column168: A phone call was received from a Univar Houston driver at 11:30am on Monday, July 6th regarding liquids leaking out of his trailer (13938)..He had identified the material as EDTA, a corrosive material with a Ph around 12.  The driver was at Rectorseal's dock.  He worked with Rectorseal’s receiving clerk to place absorbent on the pavement where the product was leaking in order to contain it. Hulcher Environmental Services was contacted for dispatch of a crew to the site for cleanup. Hulcher was on site at approximately 12:05pm and began cleanup.  The leaking drum was on a pallet in the left front of the trailer.  There was a stack of pallets loaded to the right side of this pallet for dunnage.  The loader had left a gap between the two pallets and the drum appeared to have “walked” to the edge of the pallet. Once it reached the edge of the pallet there was enough of a gap to allow the drum to tip.  When it tipped it struck the pallet behind it.  The pallet behind it had 2 nails sticking up. The drum was punctured by one of these nails.  All of the material was contained.  The other pallets on the trailer, and the trailer were decontaminated on site by Hulcher.  The leaking drum was placed into an overpack drum, and there were 3 drums of absorbent, PPE, paper etc generated during the cleanup.  All of these drums will be disposed of through Univar's Chemcare waste disposal services.    I inspected the pavement on the route the driver took into the customer.  EDTA turns a whitish color when it is exposed to air and dries.  Any spillage onto the pavement would have been fairly easy to detect.  Since there was no sign of spillage on the pavement on the customer’s property, nor on the street near the entrance it is assumed the drum must have tipped as the driver turned into the customer’s driveway.    The cleanup job was completed at 3:40pm.. I spoke with representatives of Rectorseal to confirm they were satisfied with the cleanup.  They agreed everything was taken care of to their satisfaction.  The trailer was brought back to Univar's Brisbane St yard and unloaded.  The trailer was then sent to Service Transport for thorough decontamination.
column169: Both the Dallas and Houston Univar operations managers will review this incident with all warehouse personnel.  We will reiterate our process for utilizing proper and acceptable pallets for palletizing drums, which incompasses performing a thorough inspection of the pallet to identify any broken boards and/or protruding nails and remediate. We will also review proper load bracing with loading personnel and drivers.

column168: ON 7-5-09, OUR DRIVER HAD WENT TO LION OIL, EL DORADO, AR TO UNLOAD AND RELOADED A LOAD OF LPG TO GO TO BREAUX BRIDGE, LA. ON HIS WAY BACK FROM ARKANSAS, THE DRIVER STOPPED AT A MCDONALDS IN HOMER, LA. TO EAT DINNER. THE REASON THE DRIVER STOPPED THERE WAS BECAUSE THERE WAS A LARGE TRUCK PARKING AREA BEHIND IT. THE DRIVER AT THE, WENT BACK TO HIS TRUCK AND PROCEEDED TO LEAVE. THE DRIVER WAS DRIVING THROUGH THE PARKING LOT AND IT HAD BEEN RAINING, AND HE WENT THROUGH A POT HOLE IN THE LOT. THE DRIVER HEARD A NOISE, STOPPED AND WENT AROUND THE FRONT OF HIS TRUCK TO CHECK WHERE THE NOISE CAME FROM AND THE TRAILER WAS LAYING ON IT'S RIGHT SIDE. HE BEGAN TO INSPECT FURTHER AND THE FIFTH WHEEL HAD BROKEN AWAY FROM THE TRUCK AND WAS STILL ATTACHED TO THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE AUTHORITIES AND BEGAN THE REPORTING PROCESS. NO INJURIES, NO FATALITIES, NO OTHER VEHICLE WAS INVOLVED AND NO RELEASE OF ANY PRODUCT. THE ONLY DAMAGE TO TRAILER WAS THE HOSE TUBE ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF TRAILER. OTHER THAN FIFTH WHEEL, THE TRUCK SUFFERED NO OTHER DAMAGE. LOUISIANA HAZMAT WAS CALLED IMMEDIATELY. THEY IN TURN SENT TROOPER JAY HARDY FROM TROOP A, LA STATE POLICE TO SCENE. ASHLEY BELLE FROM DEQ WAS PRESENT AT SCENE. A HOMER POLICE OFFICER AND A CLAIRBORNE SHERIFF DEPUTY WAS ALSO THERE. TRACY JONES, DUFOUR PETROLEUMS MAINTENANCE TECHNICIAN WAS ALSO ON SCENE. 3 WRECKERS AND A FIRE TRUCK WERE ON SCENE WHEN TRAILER WAS LIFTED AND SET UPRIGHT. TRAILER WAS OFFLOADED, WITH STRICT SUPERVISION BY TROOPER, TECHNICIAN AND DRIVER TO ENSURE SAFETY OF ALL CONCERNED. TRAILER WAS REMOVED FROM SCENE AND TAKEN TO NEAREST COMPANY LOCATION AND ESCORTED BY STATE TROOPER. DURING ENTIRE INCIDENT NO PRODUCT WAS LOST. DURING PROCESS ALL VALVES AND TUBING WAS CHECKED AND RECHECKED TO ENSURE THAT NO LEAKS OR CRACKS HAD OCCURRED.
column169: I HAVE NO RECOMMENDATIONS AT THIS TIME, DUE TO THIS WAS A PRODUCT FAILURE, AS IN THE FIFTH WHEEL ON THE TRUCK BROKE. IT WAS NOT A PACKAGE FAILURE.

column168: A box truck containing hazardous materials was enroute from the shippers location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at Clean Harbors in transit storage facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities of material onto a signle vehicle for continued transportation.  Upon unloading, it was discovered that 3 x 55 gallon containers had a small amount of liquid escaping fro the top closure device.  The material that escaped was contained on the top of the drums and did not ipact the floor of the trailer. An emergency response crew was immediately assembled and after donning the appropriate personal protective equipment,entered the trailer.  The crew secured the closure devices which were loose and wipped up the material that had been released with absorbent pads which were containerized and propoerly disposed of.  The container, once resecured, were trans loaded and shipped to the intended waste management facility.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, the driver has been retrained on the requirements to inspect each container before accepting for transportation to ensure the closure devices are in place and the containers are free of residual contamination.  IN addition, the driver recieved a documented warning letter for his actions as this was a preventable event.

column168: While unloading the nightly shuttle, employee was removing a pallet of 55 gl drums from trailer.  As the pallet was being pulled backwards with a forklift, a 15 gl drum of hydrochloric acid had shifted in transport and was resting on the pallet being moved.  As the pallet was removed, the 15 gl HCL drum fell 4 inches from the pallet and onto the floor, causing the bung to dislodge from the top of the drum, and emptying the contents of the drum onto the trailer floor.  The release was absorbed and neutralized with soda ash and remediated completely within one hour.  Heavy rains occurred immediately after clean up activities.  Ph readings were taken at the property outfall and confirmed to be neutral.
column169: While unloading trailer, more attention should be paid to surrounding freight, to account for unavoidable product shift during transport.    Filler to ensure that closures are tight and in good repair.     Party loading trailer and driver to ensure that entire load is secure and that transit shifting of these drums is reduced as much as possible.

column168: An employee was loading drums onto a trailer using a forklift.  The drums were being double stacked in the trailer.  The employee stacked a set of drums on top of another set, and when he backed out, the drum on top was not correctly balanced and fell off of the lower drum onto the trailer floor.  The open top lid on the drums was dislodged upon impact with the floor.  Approximately 25 gallons was spilled onto the floor, and of the 25 gallons, approximately 10 gallons leaked through the trailer floor onto asphalt.  The material was cleaned up with floor dry.
column169: The employee that was loading the drums was retrained to ensure the top drums are stable before backing out.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was enroute from the shipper's locsation to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the vehicle made a routine stop at a Clean Harbor's in-transit storage location.  During a routine inspection at this location, it was discovered that a small amount of liquid was dripping from the van trailer.  Facility personnel immediately notified local managment and an emergecny reposne crew was assembled.  After surveying the trailer and donning appropriate personnel protective equipment, it was discovered that a 55 gallon container had a split in the seamof the drum allowing approximately 10 gallons of material to leak onto the trailer floor. The damaged container was placed into a suitable salvage container and the material released to the trailers floor was absorbed using a suitable absorbent material.  The clean-up debris along with the samll amount of gravel impacted under the trailer and the material used to decontaminate the trailer floor was placed into the salvage drum which was subsequently sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.      While the spill respone was in progress, the State Agency responsible for the oversight of licensed hazardous waste transporters was mtofied on the incident and the steps taken to address the release.
column169: TAT the time the container was accepted for transprtation, no evidence of leaking, damage or overpressurization was observed.  It is believed that during transportation and storage, the container overpressurized allowing the seam to split.  It is believed that sufficient head space was not left in the container to allow for normal expansion of material during the rigors of transportation.  In order to prevent a recurrence, the shipper has been advised to ensure sufficient headspace is left in a container to accomodate any expected presuure build-up during transportation and storage.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was enroute from the shippers location to the intended waste managment facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop a a Clean Harbor's in transit storage location for the purpose of consolidating less than truckload quantities of containers onto a single vehicle for continuing transportation.  As the personnel responsible for transfering the containers iniittaed the operation, it was discovered that a 55 gallon container had tipped onto its side during transportation.  When the container was placed in an upright position, material escaped from the package onto the floor of the van trailer. An emergency response team donned the appropriate personal protctive equipment and initiated response activities.  The damaged container was placed into a suitable salvage drum along with all material used to both contain and absorb all freee liquids and the material used to decontaminate the trailer floor.  Once secured, the container was placed into an alternate vehicle for continued transportation to the intended waste management facility.
column169: A review f the incident concluded that inadequate blocking and bracing was deploted to secure the drum in question.  BOth the shipper and the driver accepting the load for transportation were advised of the incident and were requested to ensure that all future lods prepared for transportation are secured in such a way that there will be no movement, in any direction, during transportation.  In addition, the driver was advised that a repeat incident will result in disciplianry actions.

column42: SULFURIC ACID, FUMING WITH LESS THAN 30 PERCENT FREE SULFUR TRIOXIDE
column168: DRiver woke up in the morning and went to pre-trip his trailer.  As he walked around the trailer he noticed smoke / vapors coming from the dome lid of the trailer.  We immediately notified the fire department who dispatched a team to the scene.  Driver evacuated drivers around the vacinity and stayed up wind.  Fire department was able to establish that there was a problem with the gasket that allowed moisture from rain the night before to get in the space between the gasket and dome lid.  Fuming sulfuric reacts with water which caused the visible reaction and off-spout of poisonous gas.  From there we called in our emergency response team who was able to install a new gasket.  The original gasket was not the correct one that should have been in the trailer.  It requires a Viton B gasket and a braided teflon rope gasket was what was in the trailer.  Once the correct gasket was installed the situation was rectified.
column169: Our safety department was not given adeqaute time, notification, communication to review this last minute exotic commodity (fuming sulfuric acid).  Our safety team plays an intregal role in ensuring safety for every new chemical we move.  Several things can occur as a result of last minute planning such as utilizing wrong equipment or improperly trained/briefed drivers.  In this case the gaskets in the dome lid of the trailer were the wrong type.  We have discussed with leadership that the usual/correct process was not followed and a a costly evacuation (thankfully without injuries) and clean up occurred as a result.  Leadership agree's and has reviewed this process with all leaders and associates relavant in making haul/no haul decisions.

column168: On July 3, 2009 at approximately 06:30 hrs., CSX personnel discovered TILX 110092, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, leaking from the non-reclosing safety relief device. The car was isolated and the shipper, PPG Industries, was contacted via Chemtrec (Report # 2009070300043). SPSI, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the rupture disk had deployed. Further inspection determined the Salco 'Quick Inspect Safety Vent' was not equipped with the recommended surge protection device. The leak was secured and a new rupture disk was installed.     An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Non conformance Report was not completed for this incident.  Note: This incident did not require a special shipping move.    Cause Code: 441  NARRI: 2(5+5+0) x (2+0) = 40

The IMTT Environmmental Compliance Manager contacted EQ-Terminal Services to respond to the area and clean up the spilled fuel on the roadway. column168: A box truck made a pickup of a drum of hazardous waste at the generator's location and proceeded to the next location for another pickup.  When he opened the rear door of the truck he noticed a dark ring on the floor of the truck around the base of the drum.  The bolt of the lock ring, which appeared to be tight at the time of pickup, had loosened.  The driver donned the appropriate PPE, cleaned up the material with absorbent pads, and tightened the drum properly.  No material had leaked out of the truck.  The truck then proceeded to the truck transfer facility, where the drum was re-examined and then loaded onto a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: At the time of pickup, the driver inspected the drum and there was no evidence of leaking or damage. It is beleived that during transportation, the drum closure loosened.  The generator was notified that the drum was not closed properly and the driver was re-trained on drum inspections at the time of pickup and proper drum closure instructions.

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste arrived at the intended waste disposal facility.  While checking in the load, it was noticed that a small amount of liquid was leaking from the nose of the trailer.  The trailer was immediately checked in and taken to the receiving area which is in containment and unloaded.  The appropriate personal protective equipment was donned by the crew unloading the trailer who determined the leaking drum contained various bottles of pesticides and herbicides picked up at a household hazardous waste event.  A few of the bottles had leaked inside the drum which leaked at the bottom seam.  The shipment was then disposed of at the intended waste disposal facility.  The trailer was cleaned with a suitable cleaning compound and returned to service.
column169: The origin location was contacted and the personnel who loaded the drum at the household hazardous waste event were reinstructed as to proper procedures in loading and packing drums for shipment.

column168: Upon arrival to the service center, the driver noticed a smell coming from his trailer. He reported the issue and was instructed to back the trailer against the service center for further inspection. The trailer was opened and the damage notated.The shipment consisted of 48 - 5 gallon pails stacked on top of each other. The shipment was loaded last on the trailer. In order for the shipment to fit, the shipment was loaded into the trailer with extreme pressure which caused the cans to dent and crease. Overtime, the down force pressure from the other loaded cans and the crease, the cans developed holes which enabled the liquid to leak out of the cans.
column169: The loader should be counselled for his loading technique. Also the amount of pails loaded on top of the same could have been a contributing factor in the the creases being made in the cans.

column168: Shipment was braced @ origin. Additional load bars and plywood were applied. At some point between departure and arrival @ consignee the additional bracing became insufficient and several of the canisters on wheels tipped and began to vent. At consignee location, leak was discovered and trailer was immediately left open to vent. Due to the nature of the product personal injury risk was low. No evacuation or isolation was necessary. Only damage to physical containers was gauge damage, the amount of product leaked is unknown due to the nature of the liquid nitrogen turning to gas upon release and was estimated through Ibs to liquid conversion, and the fact that four of the canisters were involved. Duration of release is estimated @ 2 hours, and completely eliminated upon the canisters being repositioned vertically.
column169: Additional emphasis needs to be passed on to all employees in regards to the importance of ownership of the freight in their possession. Not so much additional awareness, simply taking more time to assess what it is being transported and to see what more can or could be done to ensure proper handling, transport and delivery of said material. Having the appropriate tools on hand to ensure the commitment of exception free delivery of our customers material (hammer, nails, bracing wood, proper load locking material, straps etc. is absolutely critical.

column168: According to the information provided, the following occurred.  While at consignee location, the dome lid came off the tank truck.  Approximately 35 gallons of sodium hydroxide solution were released.  The free product released to the asphalt surface within the consignee lot.  Motiva Enterprises personnel utilized water to wash the affected area.  The contaminated rinse water ran into the sump tank at the facility, which is designed to catch runoff and waste water.  No further cleanup was required.  Sixteen (16) Motiva Enterprises employees complained of various symptoms of exposure.  All responded to the nurse’s station on site, following the incident.  Upon investigation, they washed their faces, as a precautionary measure, and returned to work.
column169: Since the release appears to be related to equipment failure to the dome lid on the tank truck, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Slay Transportation Co., Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel, and perform routine equipment maintenance.

column168: At approximately 1530 hrs on Wednesday, July 29, 2009 a PTRA Carman working the air on track 202 at the PTRA American Yard discovered product running down the side of tank car TILX 261562. The spilled product was limited to the tank car body mostly. A small amount, several small drops, of product was found on the ballast. Upon further investigation it was discovered that the product was leaking from the manway cover.  The car was set out to track 210 and the Care of Party (Houston Fuel Oil Terminal) and Freight Bill Party (Tauber Oil Co) were notified of the condition of the car.  Houston Fuel Oil initially stated that Tauber would clean the car and determine the cause of the leak. Eventually, on Thursday 7/30 at approximately 1600 hrs Houston Fuel Oil notified the PTRA that they would send Oil Mop, Inc over to clean the car on Friday, July 31 in the early AM.  Oil Mop arrived on scene at approximately 0845 Friday and began to wipe down the product on the hand rails, ladders and side of the tank car. They determined that the shipper, Suncor Energy, failed to install a gasket on the manway allowing product to slosh out of the tank car when moved.  Approximately two gallons of product was spilled down the sides and on top of the car. Oil Mop, Inc completed the remediation and cleared the scene at 1023 hrs.
column169: Houston Fuel Oil Terminal and Tauber will be contacting the shipper to investigate the matter further.

column168: On 07/09/2009 at 1450 hrs, personnel in the CSXT Mobile, AL Terminal discovered GATX 61133, a loaded tank car of hydrochloric acid, leaking from the non-reclosing safety relief device. The car was isolated and the shipper was notified via Chemtrec (#2009070900160). The leak was secured at that time by the local CSX Hazmat Manager who determined the rupture disk had deployed. Further inspection verified the Salco 'Quick Inspect Safety Vent' was not equipped with the recommended surge suppression device.  A Dupont response team from New Johnsonville, TN responded, arriving on 7/10/2009 to inspect the car and installed a new rupture disk and assembly . Railcar Services then performed a leak test and SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene on 07/10/2009 to decontaminate the car before released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move.    NARRI cause code = 441,  2(5+5+0) X (2+0) = 40
column169: This was a Salco safety vent housing unit. The surge protector was not in place on this unit and a non campatible material was used for the rupture disk.

column42: ACETIC ACID SOLUTION, NOT LESS THAN 50 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 80 PERCENT ACID, BY MASS
column168: On July 24, 2009 at 18:30 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Big 4 yard at Russell, KY discovered tank car, ETCX 421006, a load of Acetic Acid solution, leaking product from the top of the rail car. The rail car was switched to an area of the yard where it was isolated from CSXT employees. The shipper was notified thru Chemtrec (Report #2009-07-23-00207) and the local authorities were notified of the incident thru TEMA. A CSXT emergency response contractor, Weavertown Environmental, was dispatched to the scene and found all 8 of the manway cover securement bolts were less than tool tight. The security seal was broken by the contractor (seal # mcw093796) and the manway gasket was inspected and determined to be in good shape. The manway was closed and all manway cover securement bolts were tightened. The car was decontaminated and sent on to destination.    NARRI: 5(5+5+0) X (2+0) = 100    Cause Code: 200     No 7.1 needed    Switching charge applies.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A Quality Carriers driver noticed that ferric chloride (28% Solution) was leaking from the tanker while parked at a Flying J Truckstop located at I-95 SB exit 104 in Carmel Church, VA.  A response contractor was dispatched to the area for further investigation activities.  Once on site, it was found that the tanker liner had been leaking.  A replacement tanker was dispatched to the site while Marshall Miller (environmental contractor) worked to contain the release and obtain the necessary pumps for transfer operations.  The flow of the material began to increase while awaiting the replacement tanker.  Approxmately 300 gallons of the material had been released onto the parking lot and into the facilities retention pond.  Once the replacement tanker arrived, transfer operations immediately began.  Once the product transfer had been completed, the impacted area of asphalt was neutralized and the materials were collected for disposal activities.  The affected retention pond was neutralized utilizing sodium bicarbonate and the area was vacuumed from the surface to collect the foam that had accumulated on the pond surface as a result of the neutralization activities.

column168: While securing equipment on an adjacent track, CN transportation department employees reported observing product coming from the protective housing and running down the side of tank car DOWX 73053(L/ STYRENE MONOMER, STABILIZED) at the CN Champaign Yard, Urbana, IL.  All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated in track. Three CN employees reported being exposed to product vapor and requested medical treatment. All employees were treated at a local hospital and released without restrictions. CN response team responded, noting the protective housing shipper's seal intact and product being forced past the liquid eduction valve plug.  Valve handle in the closed position, plug less than tool tight. Teflon tape applied to plug threads and plug secured stopping leak. column168: BNSF Assistant Director Hazardous Material observed FPAX 931148 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) with a small amount of dried product near the base of the safety vent/frangible disc housing. FPAX 931148 was previously spotted in the railyard on a Team track in conjunction a hazardous material training session. Detailed inspection by this responder revealed that the 165 psi frangible disc had ruptured. Dried spillage was wiped and no ground impact was evident. A suitable replacement disc was shipped and applied on 7/14/09 without further incident.   The side specification stencil on FPAX 931148 indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2002 and next due in 2012.

column168: A BNSF inbound train inspection in the railyard revealed entrained AGLX 1119 (DOT 105J300W tank car) dripping product from the B-end body bolster area. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders immediately inspected AGLX 1119 and determined it was safe to move AGLX 1119 in order to isolate it in the railyard. A receptacle was placed under AGLX 1119 to catch drippage. Dripping product that impacted the ground and captured in the catch receptacles evaporated. Additional inspection of AGLX 1119 could not determine the leak source that emanated from under the tank car jacketing and dripped out near the front of the B-end body bolster adjacent to the number one wheel. It was also noted that the B-end lower jacketing was slightly buckled on both the right and left sides. Arrangements were made to transfer the remaining product within AGLX 1119 to another suitable tank car and this was accomplished on 7/14/09 without further incident. Afterwards, the product vapors within AGLX 1119 were flared off.  The side specification stencil on AGLX 1119 indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2005 and next due in 2015.
column169: No additional comments.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: GAMX 9554 (DOT 112J340W tank car) on the repair track for coupler repair in the railyard was reported emanating a product vapor hiss. Immediate inspection by BNSF Mechanical/Hazardous Material Responders revealed that the source of the vapor release was at the pressure plate connection. The pressure plate securement stud nut positions were observed with recent numbering sequence and socket markings. The responders tool tightened all pressure plate stud nuts from 1/8 to 3/8 turn with an impact wrench. Afterwards, the vapor release stopped at 1815 PDT, 7/14/09.  Intact seal removed at the protective housing was BPCHERRYPOINT 0158737 and it was replaced by seal numbered BNSF 6157088.  The side specification stencil on GAMX 9554 indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2001 and next due in 2011.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A van trailer was being loaded at the truck transfer facility with other shipments destined for the intended waste disposal facility.  After the trailer was loaded, a small leak was noticed.  The emergency response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  The trailer was unloaded until the leaking drum was located.  The drum was found to have a small pinhole leak in the side, where it had made contact with a sharp object protruding from the side of the trailer.  The drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage drum along with the spilled residue and cleaning compound used to clean up the spill.  The sharp object was removed.  The trailer loading was then completed and the trailer proceeded to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The dock workers were re-instructed to inspect trailers more carefully prior to loading.  Better care when loading trailers prevent incidents such as this.

column168: On July 29th at 11:15 am during the startup of transferring Ferric Chloride for Kemira Water Solutions, using an air compressor, product was noticed escaping between two flanges on the fitting.  The air compressor was then immediately shut down and the air lines were bled.  30 gallons of product escaped the railcar; 20 gallons of which was captured in the track pan while 10 gallons contacted the ballast between tracks 12 and 13.  The product was neutralized using bicarbonate, per the MSDS, then cleaned up and placed in a 55 gallon drum.  The drum was labeled awaiting disposal.  After investigation it was determined that: 1. The loader over-tightened the bolts on the reducer and caused the valve assembly to become off center. 2. Teflon lined flange had small cracks and chips around the outer edge due to the continuous raising and lowering of fittings from the tops of railcars to the ballast below.
column169: 1. Terminal is purchasing additional valve assemblies in 2” and 3” sizes to minimize the need to attach and detach fittings to accommodate the various sized railcar valves.  2. Retraining employees on the proper technique of uniformly using the star pattern when bolting fittings to railcars and on the importance of not over-tightening the first bolt when doing so.   3. As part of daily equipment inspection, the Teflon lining of all chemical fittings will be inspected to ensure there are no defects in the lining itself.    4. Terminal is purchasing rubberized caps to place on the bottom of valve assemblies to further prevent premature wear of Teflon lining when lowering fittings to the ballast below.

column168: GATX 62592 (DOT 111A100W5 tank car) was reported with a product vapor release and subsequent vapor mist emanating from the frangible disc area during movement in the railyard. Movement of GATX 62592 was stopped after this observation. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders confirmed that the 165 psi frangible disc was ruptured. The responders applied a temporary replacement disc so GATX 62592 could be safely moved and isolated in the railyard. A shipper contractor replaced the temporary frangible disc with an appropriate165 psi disc on 7/14/09. During the subsequent movements of GATX 62592 in the railyard, GATX 62592 was reported having another frangible disc failure. On 7/15/09, a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder replaced the ruptured frangible disc with a 165 psi Teflon/stainless steel frangible disc that was shipped to this location after the first disc failure.  It was noted at this time that the frangible disc housing assembly appeared damaged. The top inspection cap/plug was missing with its retention wire broken. The threaded portion within the assembly for the inspection plug was damaged with threads cracked. The shipper was notified and sent a tank car mechanic whom replaced the frangible disc housing assembly. After these repairs were completed, no further reports of frangible disc failures were reported.

column168: PPGX 1804 (DOT 105J500W tank car) was reported emanating product odor in the railyard. PPGX 1804 was immediately cordoned off, yard operations ceased and employees were moved away from the area to the opposite end of the railyard. Contract responders were summoned to eliminate the odor source and initiate air monitoring. The responders removed the intact seal numbered PPG 07177 from the valve protective housing cover for valve inspection. The responders found the A-end liquid valve slightly open with its closure plug not applied. This valve was immediately closed. The threads on the one inch plug were cleaned; the plug was installed and tool tightened. Product odor detection ended after securement was completed by 1017 hrs. CDT, 7/15/09. This was confirmed by air monitoring samplings. Afterwards, PPGX 1804 was moved to a remote area in the railyard for the responders to decontaminate any impacted surfaces around the valve housing area. Yard operations were resumed after an approximate three hour cessation. PPGX 1804 was decontaminated and returned available for continued transportation by 1330 hrs. CDT, 7/15/09. Seal numbered 433301 was applied to the protective housing cover.  The specification stencil on PPGX 1804 indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2006 and next due in 2016.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

On July 28, 2009 at approximately 12:49 hrs., CSX Hazardous Materials Manager S. Michael Austin discovered UTLX 208299, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S leaking from the top of the car in the Cumberland Yard. The car was inspected and the shipper, Eco Energy, was notified thru CHEMTREC (Report# 2009-07-28-00125).  It was determined the 3" to 2" liquid valve was less than tool tight and was leaking product. The valve was made tool tight and the leak stopped.  The shipper had SPSI, a certified class G facility, perform a bubble leak test on the car. The car was secured and released for transport.    An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report was not completed for this incident.  Note: This incident did not require a special shipping move.    Cause Code:  282  NARRI:  5 (5+3+0) X (2+0) = 80
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On July 30, 2009, at 09:05 hours, a car inspector for the Finger Lakes Railway was inspecting cars on the CSX to FGL Railway interchange track at Solvay Yard and found CWCX 3, a loaded tank car of Ethanol, dripping product from the bottom outlet cap.  The inspector notified the CSXT mechanical department who in turn notified the CSX PSCC and CSX HazMat departments. The shipper, Florida Distillers, Inc., was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2009-07-30-00042).  The shipper referred CSXT to the owner of the tank car, Walter Haffner, Inc.  EP+S of Vermont, a CSX emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene to make repairs.  Upon arrival, EP+S personnel tightened the bottom outlet valve cap one turn and secured the leak. Tank car CWCX 3 was interchanged to the Finger Lakes Railway for disposition and unloading. The car owner will home shop the tank car for an inspection of the bottom outlet valve.    An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report was completed for this incident.  Note: This incident did not require a special shipping move.    Cause Code: 551  NARRI:  2 (5+3+0) x (2+0) = 32
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 07/21/2009 at 14:41 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Tilford Yard, Atlanta, Georgia, discovered tank car ETCX 222607, a load of Environmentally Hazardous Substances, Liquid N.O.S (Ethylene Glycol), leaking product from the bottom of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Shell Chemical Company and Eastman Chemical Company were notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2009-07-21-00172). SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found product leaking from where the bottom outlet valve connects to the tank car around the bolts. SWS personnel contained the leak and transferred the product into tank car ETCX 222645. While performing the transfer, SWS representatives tightened several bolts that were loose on the manway cover plate. Upon finishing the transload of product, SWS personnel found that the bottom outlet flapper valve was in the open position, while the handle was in the closed position. This incident did require a special switching move.     NARRI: 2(5+1+0) X (2+0) = 24  Cause Code: 551
column169: The contents of the car was transferred to another rail car and a FRA movement approval was filed for. Recommendation for this car is to have the bottom outlet valve replaced due to the fact that when the handle shows in the closed position, the internal flapper is in the open position.

column168: A BNSF yard switch crew reported a pungent odor emanating from the north end of the railyard. The source of the odor was initially thought to be from a loaded tank car of Methyl Mercaptan, PSPX 22128. Switching operations were suspended and impacted crews were sheltered inside the yard office. BNSF contract responders were called to investigate and eliminate the odor source. Responders reported PSPX 22162 (DOT 105J500W tank car) was found to be the odor source. Responder's detection equipment registered product vapor at the pressure plate flange of PSPX 22162. Responders used an impact wrench to tool tighten the pressure plate stud nuts until their metering device registered no detectable vapor emission. Yard operations at the north end of the railyard were resumed at 1240 hrs. CDT, 7/17/09. The shipper requested PSPX 22162 to be returned to their origin loading facility for furtherance.  Maintenance history for PSPX 22162 provided by the shipper indicated that the pressure plate was last removed during its tank qualification in the year 2003.

The cap(s) were secured.  The carton was wet but otherwise undamaged.  The undamaged portion of the package was repacked for return to shipper.

Crew JB-2, which switches Johnsonburg yard and local customers, reported a leaking tank car at 1955 on 07/28/09.  The conductor reported that while switching the A-Track he noticed a tank car sloshing some liquid out of the top and the sides of the car were wet.  Also, he noticed that small amounts of liquid were dripping off of the bottom of the car into the middle of the track.  The conductor stated that the liquid was only sloshing out of the top when the car was being moved.  The A-Track paralles a stream and once it was determined that there was no danger of the liquid entering the stream and moving the car would cause more liquid to leak that leaving the car where it sat was the best option.  The car was a tank car with # GAMX 5577, UN 1824, Sodium Hydroxide Solution.  Leaving the car sit at this location posed no danger to employees, the public or environment.    Haz-Mat and environmental response company Specialized Professional Services, Inc. (SPSI) was called to assess and remidiate the situation.  They found that the tank car was leaking small amounts of liquid due to a broken rupture disk.  SPSI neatraulized the track area where liquid leaked and wiped and neautralized the sides of the car.  They then replaced the rupture disk and cleared the car for spotting and subsequent unloading.      The total amount of time the car was leaking is unknown.  At least 2 other crews switched the A-Track in the prior 24 hours before the car was found leaking and neither crew saw anything abnormal with this car.  It is suspected that while the JB-2 was switching the A-Track the rupture disk broke due to several large sloshes of the liquid in the tank car.  If this is when the rupture disk broke then total amout of time the leak would have occurred would have been approximately 6 hours.
column169: All crews on the BPRR are being contacted to refresh them on checking haz-mat cars for potential leaks and procedures to be followed if anything is found. Also, the importance of handling haz-mat cars with care is being addressed.    It is unknown if the rupture disk was defective although the car owner was notified to throulghy check all valves, fittings, gaskets etc..  before reloading cars.

column168: During the twilight shift in the Commerce City UPS Hub, employees noticed several packages on a conveyor belt that were on fire. Initial response with fire extinguishers was ineffective. The building was evacuated and fire department called The fire department extinguished the fire and allowed reoccupancy of offices at 2330 hours and the rest of the bulding at 00:50 hours. The fire department determined the source of the fire was a 5-gallon pail of methanol, which was shipped in a fiberboard overpak. The cap for the pail had come off and the majority of the fiberboard had been destroyed by fire.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility. During the course of the trip, the driver conducted a routine load check and identified  material leaking from the trailer onto the parking area of the truck stop.  The driver immediately place an absorbent material down to absorb the free liquid and prevent the spread of the release.  Once secured, he notified his home dispatcher and the manager of the fueling facility where the vehicle was parked.  The Blacksburg Fire Department was called as was a local emergency response company.  Upon arrival the emergency response team inspected the trailer and determined that it was secured pending the arrival of a Clean Harbor's Emergency Response Team. Upon arrival of Clean Harbor's personnel, the team, utilizing appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the trailer and initiated the removal of containers in order to identify the leaking container.  It was discovered that 2 separate 55 gallon drums were leaking from the bottom seam.  The crew placed the leaking containers into a suitable over pack and proceeded to absorb and collect all free liquids.  This material was placed into the salvage drums along with all materials used to decontaminate the trailer floor.  In addition, the absorbent used to collect the material that escaped from the trailer was collected and this to was placed into the salvage drums for disposal.  Once the clean up was complete, the trailer was reloaded and was sent on to the intended waste management facility where the shipment was received and processed for disposal.
column169: AT the time the containers were accepted for transporttion, no evidence of leaking was observed.  It is believed that the corrosion identified on the bottom seam of the container failed during the course of transportation allowing the material to leak from the container.  In order to prevent a recurrence, the individuals that offered the shipment for transportation and the driver in posession of the shipment have been re instructed to ensure that each drum is inspected before it is accepted for transportation.  Any container that is found to have suspect structural integrity is to be either transferred into a suitable container or placed into a salvage drum for continued transportation.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route from the shipper's location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a Clean Harbor's in transit storage facility in order to consolidate less than truckload quantities onto a single vehicle for continuing transportation.  During the tranfer operation, the fork-lift operator allowed the pallet he was moving to contact the side wall of the trailer.  This contact allowed one 55 gallon drum to fall from the pallet which cause the lid to dislodge.  Facility personnel activated the in house emergency response team and after donning appropriate personal protective equipment intiated the containment and clean-up of the paint.  All free liquid was collected and placed into an alternate container as was all material used to clean and decontaminate the trailer.  These containers where then secured and sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: In order to prevent a reoccurrence, the facility technicians responsible for loading and unloading vehicles have been retrained on the use of mechanical drum handling equipment.  An emphasis was placed on space management to ensure that all activities are performed in such a way that the containers being moved are secured to the pallet and do not come in contact with other lading or the side walls of the trailer.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported product odor emanating from CELX 6421 (DOT 111S60ALW1 tank car) in the railyard. Operations were ceased and yard crews were sheltered inside the yard office complex.  A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected CELX 6421 and reported no product odor present at or around CELX 6421. Further inspection revealed a slight product stain at the manway nozzle. The responder checked the securement of the ten manway securement bolt nuts and found several of these not tool tight.  The loose bolt nuts were tool tightened. A nearby BNSF hazardous material contractor was also called to respond. The contract responders reported finding all valves closed and secure. They also reported finding zero gauged internal pressure within CELX 6421. The manway cover was opened to check the product outage level and the manway gasket condition. The product outage was deemed appropriate. A portion of the manway gasket was observed hanging inside the manway nozzle and this gasket appeared in good condition. Since the manway gasket was misaligned or not fully seated; it was concluded that this condition along with the loose manway securement bolt nuts prevented a good manway closure seal. The manway gasket was correctly repositioned and the manway lid was closed and properly secured prior to 0700 hrs. CDT, 7/31/09. Intact seals numbered 5191439 and 5191432 were removed; replaced by seals numbered 2877021 and 2877022. Yard operations resumed after an approximate three hour outage. No further incidents were reported during subsequent rail movements of CELX 6421.    The specification stencil on CELX 6421 indicated that it was built 6/1968 and its last tank qualification was completed in the year 2008 and next due in 2018.   One BNSF employee whom was a member of the crew that reported the product odor was treated at a local hospital for inhalation exposure and released.

column168: BNSF switch crews reported a residue Pentane tank car (UTLX 200043) emanating a product odor in the railyard and this tank car was cordoned off in the railyard. BNSF and contract hazardous material responders inspected UTLX 200043 and found it secure. Additional rail car inspections in the railyard were initiated to locate the odor source. The contract responders using a PID (photo-ionization detector) reported finding UTLX 25353 (DOT 111A60W1 tank car) as the odor source. Detailed inspection of UTLX 25353 revealed that the vacuum relief valve (VRV) or vacuum breaker was the source point of the odor. The VRV's stem bottom pressure seal (o-ring) appeared displaced. The VRV was covered and sealed with nitrile material and UTLX 25353 was isolated in the railyard. The contract responders returned the morning of 7/27/09 to remove the VRV and install a steel plug in the vacated VRV orifice. After the VRV plug was secured, the responders found no readings from their PID device at or near UTLX 25353.  Three BNSF crew members whom initially reported the product odor were treated and released from a local hospital.

CHEMTREC contacted Nalco who dispatched their containment team, Hulcher Professional Svcs, Hudson, WI, who transferred the liquid into 55-gal drums until Nalco could provide a sound tote to transfer the liquid back into.  The location of the valve and the crack in it were not the cause of improper forklift handling.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported a product stain on the side shell of PLMX 30120 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) in the railyard. PLMX 30120 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. No product impacted the ground and the spillage on the side shell was evaporating. BNSF and contract hazardous material responders inspected PLMX 30120 and determined the product release source was at the 75 psi pressure relief device (PRD). A detailed inspection of the PRD revealed that the PRD bottom stem had broken off, releasing the spring assembly which was missing. The responders acquired a replacement 75 psi PRD and installed it. The replacement PRD had a SCFM air flow rate slightly less that its predecessor PRD and since no required leakproof test was completed after the new PRD was installed; a FRA Movement Approval FRA-09080330 was granted to move PLMX 30120 in rail transportation to the consignee to be unloaded. No further incidents of product release from PLMX 30120 were reported during rail transportation to the consignee.

column168: A vacuum tanker containing hazardous waste was en route fron the shippers location and arrived at the destination facility in Bristol CT. Upon arrival the driver noticed the tanker was leaking and notified plant personel. Driver placed a five gallon pail to contain the leak and spread sorbent to absorb the free liquid that had reached the pavement. The Bristol Fire Department and the CT DEP were called and notified of the spill (both parties responded). A Clean Harbors Emergency Response Team was on site within a few minutes to clean up the free liquid and sorbent utilizing proper personal protective equipment. It was discovered that the dome cover on the tanker was not secured properly. The sorbent was swept up along with the five gallon pail and recieved for processing/disposal at the Bristol facility.The tanker was secured and recieved by the Bristol facility for processing and disposal.
column169: The Bristol office conducted a manditory driver stand down training session the following morning 7/30/09 at 6am for all drivers to reveiw proper dome cover closure and vacuum tanker operating procedures. A training attendance sheet of all drivers was provided to the CT DEP.

column168: A FRA Inspector in the railyard reported observing TCIX 16035 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) with product residue on its A-end side shell. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders reported that the product spillage emanated from the pressure relief device (PRD). BNSF contract responders were summoned to check the product outage level and clean the product spill from the shell of TCIX 16035. Contract responders reported that the product outage level appeared to be appropriate. The spillage on the shell of TCIX 16035 was neutralized and wiped clean on 7/21/09. The suspected cause of this liquid product release from the PRD was attributed to a hydraulic pressure surge from movement.  The specification stencil on TCIX 16035 indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2000 and next due in 2010; and the 75 psi Safety Valve (PRD) was tested in 2007.

column168: On July 30, 2009 at CSX Transportation, Connellsville, PA, Mr. Timothy Rowan, FRA, HazMat Inspector reported while mounting UTLX 649612, load Styrene Monomer, Stabilized, he noted an odor of styrene. Mr. Rowan advised the vacuum relief valve was defective. CSX Transportation personnel contacted the shipper, Gordon Terminals, McKees Rocks, PA, Mr. Thomas Martonic (412-331-9410). Mr. Martonic advised he would contact America's Styrenics, Houston, TX (car lesser) for assistance.    On August 13, 2009, T. J. Mannas, Manager - HazMat, CSX Transportation contacted Ms. Dawn Brubaker, Logistics Manager, America's Styrenics, Houston, TX (281-203-5405 office; 979-239-8113 cell). Ms. Brubaker advised she had dispatched Rescar personnel. Rescar personnel had advised her the vacuum relief valve was removed and replaced in kind. Ms. Brubaker was proceeding to either have this fitting qualified or obtain a FRA Movement Approval to allow UTLX 649612 to continue in transportation.    On August 14, 2009, Ms. Brubaker advised that she has dispatched Specialized Professional Services, Inc., Washington, PA to qualify the installation of the vacuum relief device.  Specialized Professional Services, Inc. conducted a bubble leak test on the car on August 17, 2009. The tank car has been requalified and is ready to be released back into transportation.    An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report will be completed for this incident.  Note: This incident did require a special shipping move to shop the car at Connellsville, PA. A CSXT "HazMat" hold was placed on the car.    Cause Code: 675  NARRI:  5(5+1+0) X (2+0) = 60
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A van trailer load of drums arrived at the ten day storage facility.  The unloading of the drums had just begun when the crew notices a bulging drum.  The drum was being moved to the staging area for examination when it blew open from pressure within the drum.  A clean up crew donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the material, which was entirely within containment.  The drum was overpacked along with all cleanup materials into a suitable salvage container.  The entire shipment then proceeded to the intended waste disposal facility.

column168: Container SUDU 396169, reported leaking product at the ICTF, Long Beach, CA.  Inspection developed the lading to be a total of 80 drums, double stacked, in a twenty foot container.  The drums were secured with Ty-Gard, which was improperly applied, allowing the material to sag.  While removing the drums, located one floor loaded drum near the rear doors, that had a two inch side wall stress crack, directly above the bottom chime. The bottom chime on the opposite side of the drum, was deformed and bent upwards, indicating the drum impacted an adjacent drum during the loading process.  Estimated 6 gallons of product released.  The drum was patched and placed into a salvage drum for securement.  Near the nose of the container, on the second tier of drums, located a drum that had a slight dent on the bottom chime, that allowed product to weep through the chime.  It appears the drum chime abraded an adjacent drum during transit.  Less than one gallon of product was released.  The drum was patched and placed into a salvage drum for securement.  Two additional drums were found to have sufficient damge to warrent them unfit for further transport, and were placed into salvage drums for securement.  The container flooring was cleaned of the residue, and the remaining drums were placed back into the original container.  The lading was properly secured for movement to the port for vessel  loading.  The four salvage drums are to be returned to the shipper, per their request.
column169: Proper application of Ty-Gard - Proper loading protocol - Inspection + use of equipement used to load commodity

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: THE BATTERY WAS BEING TRANSPORTED FROM OUR CUSTOMER TO OUR SHOP FOR REPAIRS.  IT WAS ON A WOODEN PALLET FOR LOADING/UNLOADING PURPOSES, AND WAS SECURED TO THE TRUCK BY HEAVY DUTY BINDER TRAVELING OVER UNLEVEL SURFACES THE WEIGHT OF THE BATTERY CRACKED MOST OF SUPPORTING BOARDS CAUSING THE BATTERY TO TILT AND THE BINDER LOST TENSION ALLOWING THE BATTERY TO TIP OVER AND THEN EVENTUALLY SLIP OFF THE TRUCK TO THR PAVEMENT.  IT JUST SO HAPPENED THAT A FIRE TRUCK WAS AT THIS SAME INTERSECTION (NOT ON A RESPONSE CALL) AND WITNESSED THE INCIDENT.  THEY QUICKLY CONTAINED ANY SPILLAGE WITHIN MINUTES.  THE TOTAL AMOUNT OF ACID SPILLED FROM THE BATTERY CELLS WAS APPROXIMATELY 1/2 TO 1 PINTS.  THE INDIVIDUAL CELLS DID NOT RUPTURE, ALL SPILLAGE CAME THROUGH THE VENT CAPS.  THE FIRE DEPT. HAD SAND AND ALSO BAKING SODA ON BOARD THEIR VEHICLE, SO THE ACID WAS NEUTRALIZED IMMEDIATELY.
column169: THIS PARTICULAR BATTERY IS TALLER THAN THE MAJORITY OF BATTERIES THAT WE TRANSPORT.  FOR THE IMMEDIATE REACTION, WE WILL NOT US PALLETS ON THESE BATTERIES.  WE WILL HAVE A NON-SKID MATT ON THE TRUCKBED AND ALWAYS HAVE TWO BINDERS.  STEP 2 WILL INCLUDE GETTING SOME SUPPORTS DESIGNED TO NOT ALLOW THE BATTERY TO TILT OR FALL OFF THE TRUCKBED.  IN CONJUNCTION WITH THE BINDERS THE BATTERY SHOULD BE ABLE TO STAND ALL TYPES OF BUMPY AND UNLEVEL SURFACES.

column168: Lane Sekavec, Manager Hazardous Materials responded to a release of liquid from MHFX 5103 at the One-Spot car repair facility in Kansas City, KS. Inspection of the area revealed a green-tinted liquid had run out of the car after it had been jacked up. Inspection of the inside of the car failed to identify a source for the liquid; however, the bulkheads securing the load in each end of the car had failed, allowing the load to shift. Mr. Sekavec made contact with the shipper to advise them of the incident and the condition of the car. Shipper advised the car would be transloaded on August 10th and the contents would be inspected then. On August 10th and 11th, the car was partially unloaded, contents inspected with no source of a release found, and then reloaded and secured. The liquid that had been released the night of the original incident had been absorbed with clay absorbent and placed into buckets. The buckets were placed with the original shipment for disposal at destination. During the reloading, 77 drums of materials other than those originally billed were found, necessitating additions to the shipping paperwork. Following securement and the required paperwork corrections, the car was released to continue in transportation. Hazardous Waste Manifest Numbers 100031653CTN and 100031655CTN.
column169: Ensure the shipper performs proper blocking and bracing.

column168: Unit 5157 was travelling on 1-94 in Doltin Ii. The driver went over a section of highway that was being paved and the tank failed in front of the middle hatch area. The metal on top of the tank failed causing the tank to buckle. The leak occurred at the top of the tank and continued until the liquid level in the tank got below the failed section.   After the driver realized what had transpired, he found a safe area to pull over, deployed his spill kit and called 911 to initiate a response. Local fire, hazmat and response teams where mobilized and a plan of action was determined to off load the remaining contents of the tank into another tanker. The product was then returned to the shipper for storage.   It is still unclear why the tank failed and we are still investigating why the failure occurred. Pictures are attached. After the outer skin of this tanker is taken off further investigation will be done along with pictures to document the damage will be obtained.

column168: Our vehicle was traveling north on I-75 when a car traveling in the same direction lost control and broadsided our vehicle, forcing our vehicle off of the roadway, and into a jack knife as it traveled across the freeway to the center medium wall. The momentum of our vehicle meeting the wall caused our trailer to overturn and break away from the tractor. The gasoline and diesel fuel spilled from the trailer, catching fire and burning our truck/trailer, a Meijers truck. trailer and also the car that caused the crash. As a result of the fire, the bridge that carries 9 Mile Rd. traffic collasped. There were no serious injuries and no fatalities. Police and fire crews were called to the scene to fight the fire and to direct traffic away from the accident. At that time the Michigan Sate Police took charge of the accident scene. The fire lasted for several hours. There was not enough of the trailer left to really tell which part of the unit failed first letting the gas and diesel to spill. We can only surmise that when the trailer turned on its side and slid on the road surface it may have ruptured.
column169: We have made our drivers aware of all the details of the incident so they can be more careful when traveling that stretch of highway. I have encouraged them to be even more attentive to traffic befor entering the curves. I have encouraged my drivers to drive more defensively when eratic driving is noticed and to steer away from such behavior as much as possible.

column168: Train #136 with controlling locomotive DMVW 9413 traveling north to Max, ND derailed 7 cars at 21:15 at M.P. 469 or approximately 2 miles south of Max. 1 tank car (WCHX 30049) was tipped over and resting on the dome. This carwas not leaking at this time. 6 cars loaded with distillers dried grains (DDG) were broken open and product was spilled onto the ground. ND State Radio was notified of the situation. Upon inspection of the derailment site the next morning, it was discovered that the tank car had developed a slow leak at the flange on the fill hole. DMVW Railroad Mechanical Department built a containment dike around the leaking car. Earthmovers of Minot, ND took over there-mediation and clean up work. Primary cause of the derailment was determined to be a base break in a section of72.02 Ib rail.
column169: The 72-lb rail at the derailment site was laid in 1898. This rail is scheduled to be replaced later this year or early in 2010. There are 3 miles of 72-lb rail in this section of track.

column168: TRIMAC DRIVER WAS TRAVELING ON HIGHWAY 36 EAST WHEN HE MADE A WRONG TURN ONTO HIGHWAY 42 WEST.  CONDITIONS WERE HEAVY RAIN AND FOG THAT MORNING IN THE EARLY HOURS.  DRIVER TRAVELED FROM CARROLLTON FOR ABOUT 40 MINUTES LOOKING FOR AN AREA TO STOP AND CHECK HIS DIRECTIONS AND COULD NOT FIND A SAFE PLACE.  SO HIS DECISION WAS TO CHECK HIS DIRECTION WIHILE DRIVING, HE TURNED ON HIS DOME LIGHT IN CAB AND WAS READING HIS GOOGLE DIRECTION WHEN HE DROPPED OFF THE SHOULDER OF HIGHWAY 42 AND LOST CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE.  HE WAS 2.5 MILES FROM BEDFORD, KY WHERE HE COULD HAVE PARKED AND MADE A U TURN SAFETY.  UNIT OVER TURNED ON THE SHOULDER OF HIGHWAY 42 CAUSING THE PRODUCT TO BROKE THE 6" RUPTURE DISK AND RELEASING THE PRODUCT.  THE SHOULDER FILLED WITH PRODUCT AND FLOWED OVER THE ROADWAY INTO AN OPEN FIELD BECAUSE THE WATER DRAIN UNDER THE  ROADWAY WAS TOO SMALL TO HANDLE THE FLOW.  THE DRIVER EXITED THE TRACTOR AND WALKED TO A HOUSE TO CALL 911.  THIS IS A REVISED REPORT DUE TO MAILING AN OUTDATED FORM.

column42: COMPOUND, CLEANING, LIQUID (CONTAINING PHOSPHORIC ACID, ACETIC ACID, SODIUM HYDROXIDE OR POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE)
column168: At 10:00 Jackie Eckenrode received a call from Mark at Wal-Mart in Conway, AR.  Untited States Environmental Services L.L.C. was called by Jim Race to assist in the clean up.  The clean up crew arrived at 12:00 PM.  They determined it was a chlorinated alkaline cleaner(AFCO NAME Power Foam CL NP NO.5333).  The product was being shipped in an IBC.  265 gallons was being shipped, with a max capacity of 275 gallons for the tote.  10 gallons had leaked onto the floor of the trailer and dripping out onto the pavement.  Natures Broom(quick dry) was used to soak up material that was leaking.  At 2:30 the leaked was stopped and contained.  The valve was leaking. Estimated duraction of leak is 10:00am till 2:30pm.
column169: Each driver has been retrained on spills and how to prevent them from happening with a JJ Keller course.  The training was given on August 13-15th. Each driver had to watch a 30 minute video and as a whole we reviewed questions that was given with the video, and any questions that each driver might have had.    All employees are taking a part in double checking everything that leaves our facility to help prevent incidents in the future.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, A FIVE GALLON PAIL OF LIQUID WAS PUNCTURED AND DAMAGED BY FORKLIFT BLADE.  THE PAIL AND AFFECTED MATERIAL WERE PLACED INTO PROPER MARKED, LABELED AND LINED SALVAGE DRUMS.  THE DRUMS ARE BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION.
column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. CHECK BRAKES FOR PROPER AND SAFE USE. IF ATTACHMENTS USED FOR FORKLIFT ARE IMPROPERLY WORKING, THEY MUST BE REMOVED FROM SERVICE AND BE REPAIRED OR TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE PERMANENTLY. MAINTENANCE MUST BE DONE PROPERLY TO ENSURE SAFETY USE FOR ALL. WHEN ENTERING OR EXITING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS, OR TOTES LOADED OR STACKED ON THE FLOOR; ON A PLATFORM AND OR HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OFSURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING. LEAVE PAIL OF HAZARDOUS OR CHEMICAL IN THE BAY UNTIL TRAILER IS READY FOR CLOSE. EMPLOYEE GIVEN COACHING ON LOADING AND DOCK AWARENESS

column168: Transport vehicle was involved in a motor vehicle accident. The transport vehicle swerved to avoid another vehicle that was pulling out onto the two lane roadway and went into the transport vehicle lane of travel. The transport vehicle went off of the roadway to the right and turned over. The materials were in an intermodal container and some of the 5 gallon drums were damaged in the collision.The majority of the time spent at the scene was spent uprighting the transport vehicle and stabilizing the load in the container to be able to safely transport the load to the destination for further processing and assessment of damages.Some of the product did leak from the container onto the ground. 15 yards of contaminated soil were removed and transported to the East Texas Regional Landfill.
column169: Drivers are reminded to keep a proper lookout and drive defensively in order to attempt to avoid collisions. The use of load stabilizers inside the container might have prevented any damage to the packaging inside the container.

column168: On July 28, 2009, Steve Knight loaded his truck and left to make deliveries in Kentucky and Ohio. While he was traveling on US 460 to his first stop, he observed a group of cars coming towards him. He noticed one car starting to drift toward the center line. Steve does not know if the car crossed over the line.  Steve moved to the right and his tire went off the edge of the road. Steve took his foot off of the gas, did not brake, and tried to keep his truck going straight till he could ease it back onto the road. Steve’s tire hit a concrete culvert and at this point he lost control of his vehicle. The tractor and trailer went to his left, onto the road and ended up on its side completely across the road.  The driver of the jeep struck Steve head on and came to a rest on the grass. She was taken by ambulance for observation and was later released.  A car, traveling in the same lane, behind Steve ran off the road. The driver, of the vehicle following our vehicle, told Steve he had to run off the road to avoid hitting him.  Several people stopped to check on Steve and the woman. Steve was able to get out of the vehicle and he called the office and spoke with his direct Supervisor, Preston Porter,  Local police, Fire, EMT’s and the Scott county Hazmat team were sent to the scene.  Brenntag sent Preston Porter and Jeff Brown to the Scene.  They were later joined by:  Ken Jones V.P. Operations  Bob McCutchan Indy District Operations Mgr,  Chris Dawson Georgetown Distribution Center Mgr.  Responders arrived on the Scene shortly after 8:00 and clean up was done by 10:30 pm. In the course of that time the following was done:  Steve was taken from the scene; drug tested, and checked over by a Physicians Assistant at Georgetown Worxs.  The driver of the jeep bad to be cut out of car due to the door being jammed. She walked to the ambulance, where she was taken to the hospital. I was later told she had minor injuries and was released.    The Fire Department, Homeland Security Director, Scott County Hazmat team, and Brenntag Mid-South, Inc. worked together to: establish a safe perimeter; determine the best way to clean up the spilled material; remove the non spilled material, and the damaged vehicles.  Evergreen Environmental was called in to handle the clean up  A 3 mile section of 460 was closed, from Centerville road to Newton Pike.  The initial perimeter was several hundred yards away but KU reported a spark at their sub-station, located adjacent to the scene of the accident, so the perimeter was moved out to approximately 1/2 mile.  (The trailer had struck a small portion of the fence and KU came out and replaced this)  At approximately 4:00 p.m. Evergreen and Brenntag started the process of removing the damaged material, good material, and damaged vehicles.  At approximately 10:30 Evergreen finished cleaning the site and the road was open to traffic.  Evergreen came back to the site the following day to fill in the holes on the side of the road. They ha
column169: 1) WE SENT OUT A SAFETY ALERT TO ALL PERSONNEL ON THE DATE OF THE INCIDENT TO HELP RAISE AWARENESS AS A PREVENTIVE MEASURE.   2) WE HAVE EVALUATED THE FACTORS INVOLVED SUCH AS A TWO-LANE ROAD WITH LIMIITED SHOULDER FOR AVOIDING ACCIDENTS.  WE ARE LOOKING AT REROUTING OUR TRUCK DELIVERIES IN THIS AREA.  3) WE WERE PLEASED WITH HOW WELL THE PACKAGING SURVIVED THE VEHICLE CRASH.  WE WILL CONTINUE OUR EFFORTS TO ENSURE LOAD SECUREMENT MEETS DOT REQUIREMENTS DURING INITIAL AND RECCURENT TRAINING.  THE RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS     COULD HAVE BEEN WORSE IF THE CONTAINERS WERE NOT PROPERLY SECURED.  4) PICTURES WERE TAKEN FOR OUR INTERNAL INVESTIGATION AND WILL USED AS A SOURCE OF INFORMATION TO IMPLEMENT FURTHER PREVENTIVE MEASURES AS WE CONDUCT OUR SAFETY MEETINGS WITH OUR PERSONNEL.

column168: On 07-23-09 at about 4:30 pm I received a call in reference to a traffic accident that occurred at 3:57pm 9 miles south of Johnson Ks. on Hwy 27. According to Guy and Justin, Todd Gasseling, was driving his 2008 Ford Pickup Unit #221 south on Hwy 27 pulling one nurse tank #81 when he either blew a front tire or lost a front wheel on the nurse tank trailer causing the trailer and pickup to roll over. The tank was separated from the trailer and during the accident the valves were broken off causing an anhydrous ammonia release. The nurse tank is a 1000-gallon vessel filled to 85%. When the broken valves were plugged there was less than 10% left in the tank. This would mean that about 750 gallons or 3862 lbs were released into the atmosphere. By the time I learned of the accident, Justin Ochs was already making the necessary spill reporting calls, David and Guy were on scene as was the Sheriff Dept and LEPC.    The next day I inspected the truck at the Sheriff’s impound and spoke to the officer that worked the accident. He stated that Todd was traveling south on Hwy 27 about 9 miles south when he lost the right front wheel on the NH3 trailer. Todd told him that he was driving at about 55mph when the accident happened. The loss of the wheel caused the truck and trailer to pull towards the ditch and when it reached the ditch the trailer and truck both rolled over. At some point during the accident the NH3 tank became separated from trailer and ended up about 50 yards off the highway. Todd was wearing a safety belt. No one else was injured and no property was damaged. No one was evacuated and traffic was not diverted due to the loss of Ammonia. LEPC was on scene. The wind was blowing to the Southwest at 5 –10 mph.
column169: Driver was disciplined and drivers were warned to slow down and the speed rated on the tires.

column168: Driver caught the edge of the pavement which caused him to fishtail and leave the roadway. This caused the vehicle to overturn which ruptured the tank and spilled asphalt into a small stream. Response teams were on the scene within about an hour. The asphalt solidified upon contact with the water and the response teams were able to contain the product within a few hundred yards of the truck/accident. Remaining product was pumped from the wrecked truck and returned to the shipper.  Remediation crews restored the site within a few days to it's natural state.

column168: TANK TRAILER HAD FINISHED DELIVERY.  DRIVER AND HELPER WAS ROLLING UP HOSE AND RELIEVING PRESSURE FROM TANK WHEN THEY SAW PRODUCT LEAKING FROM BOTTOM OF TANK.  DRIVER DISCOVERED A HOLE APPROXIMATELY 1" IN DIAMETER IN THE STEEL COVER ON THE BOTTOM CLEAN-OUT FLANGE.  THE COVER IS A RUBBER COVERED CIRCULAR STEEL BLANK DISC,, BOLTED TO THE BOTTOM OF THE FLANGE.  IT IS REMOVED UNLESS THE TRAILER MUST BE COMPLETELY DRAINED.  THE HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDING TO THE INCIDENT, PLUGGED THE HOLE.  THE PRODUCT WAS THEN TRANSFERRED TO TWO OTHER AVAILABLE TANK TRUCKS SENT TO OFF-LOAD THE REMAINING PRODUCT.  PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED BY USE OF AN ELECTRIC SUBMERSIBLE PUMP.  THE TANK TRAILER ORIGINALLY WAS LOADED TO 4200 GALLONS.  THE FIRST DELIVERY WAS 250 GALLONS.  APPROXIMATELY 3800 GALLONS + / -50 GALLONS WERE OFF-LOADED TO TWO OTHER TANKERS.
column169: BEFORE COMPANY ENFORCEMENT OF COMPANY MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL TO ADHERE TO MAINTENANCE SCHEDULES.  BETTER COMPANY TRAINING AWARENESS FOR DRIVERS AND MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL OF THEIR RESPONSIBILITY.  BETTER COMPANY COMMUNICATION TO ALL PERSONNEL THAT THERE ARE NO REPRISALS FOR TAKING EQUIPMENT "OUT OF SERVICE" IF THEY DISCOVER THE EQUIPMENT IS OUT OF TEST, OR NO COMPLIANCE IN ANY WAY.  IMPROVE OPERATING PROCEDURES TO INSURE NO ONE SINGLE PERSON SIGNS OFF ON VEHICLE INSPECTIONS.  THE CERTIFIED INSPECTED INSPECTOR MUST RECEIVE A COUNTER SIGNATURE TO RETURN THE EQUIPMENT TO SERVICE.

column168: On Sunday, July 26, 2009, at 1055 lost control of his vehicle while rounding a curve in the roadway.  The vehicle struck the guardrail, a telephone junction box, and a fence.  A subsequent explosion/fire damaged a parked motor vehcile, two electrical power poles, several trees, and the house located on the property adjacent to the roadway.  Crash #500110528 is a one-vehicle, two prson fatality.  The temperature was eighty-four degrees with sero precipitation.  This crash was caused by our driver traveling too fast to negotiate a sharp left hand curve in the roadway, causing the tanker trailer to overturn, pulling the tractor with it (the curve had a recommended speed of 35 mph).    Hanser's Environmental Remediation cleaned up the release.  telephone number:  406-248-7795  addreess:  430 South Billings Blvd; Billings, Montana 59101
column169: Defensive driving, being aware of your surroundings, paying attention to road signs can not be emphasized enough.

column168: THIS INCIDENT OCCURED WHEN A PASSENGER VEHICLE WAS SEEN OPERATING RECKELESSLY (SPEEDING & SWERVING, ETC.) IN TRAFFIC NORTH BOUND ON INTERSTATE 95, NEWBURGPORT, MASS. ON 7/6/09.  APPROXIMATELY 50 YARDS IN FRON OF MY TRUCK AND FUEL TRAILER THIS PASSENGER VEHICLE WAS SPEEDING AND SWERVING IN TRAFFIC WHEN IT LOST CONTROL MOVING LEFT AND FLIPPING OVER ONE LANE INTO THE GRASSY MEDIUM BETWEEN I-95 SOUTH AND NORTH.  THIS CAUSED A CHAIN REACTION AS THE CAR IMMEDIATELY IN FRONT OF MY TRUCK DRIVER LOCKED THEIR BRAKES INTO A SKID.  THIS FORCED MY TRUCK DRIVER TO LOCK HIS BRAKES INTO A SKID.  DURING THE SKID MY DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO AVOID STRIKING OTHER VEHICLES AND SWITCHD LANES.  HIS TRUCK AND TRAILER ROLLED OVER ONTO THE ROAD AND A LEAK BEGUN THE BACKS, CURB SIDE OF THE FUEL TRAILER.  THE RELEASE OCCURRED FOR ABOUT 4 1/2 HRS. UNTIL THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT ALLOWED THE TRAILER TO BE SAFELY "UPRIGHTED".  ONCE UPRIGHTED THE LEAK STOPPED AND THE REMAINING CONTENTS IN THE FUEL TRAILER WAS PUMPED OFF.  THE EXTRA GASOLINE LEAK WAS CLEANED UP BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR.  THE PASSENGER VEHICLE THE CAUSED THE ACCIDENT WAS CITED.  MY DRIVER WAS NOT CITED.
column169: BASED UPON THE CIRCUMSTANCES THAT CAUSED THIS INCIDENT WE HAVE NO SUGGESTIONS TO HELP PREVENT RECURRENCE OF THE EVENTS THAT CAUSED THIS ACCIDENT.  SIMPLY, THIS WAS AN UNPREVENTABLE ACCIDENT BY MY TRUCK DRIVER WHO WAS OBEYING ALL MOTOR VEHICLE REGULATIONS AND WAS AT THE WRONG PLACE AT THE WRONG TIME.  PREDICTING A MOTOR VEHICLE IN FRONT OF YOU WILL ABRUTLY CROSS LANES, FLIP OVER, AND CAUSE A CHAIN REACTION CANNOT BE TAUGHT.  IT IS ALL ABOUT REACTION AND AVOIDING STRIKING ANOTHER VEHICLE.  WOULD RECOMMEND LEGISLATION MANDATING LARGER FINES AND LONGER LICENSE REVOCATIONS FOR THOSE WHO RECKLESSLY OPERATE ALL MOTOR VEHICLES.

column168: While unloading bags to the inbound belt from 896 a bag (AA659856) was smoking.  Further investigation revealed the bag contained several bottles of unlabeled liquids, some of which had leaked, and several plant or agricultural type products.  The bag had a strong smell of vinegar emanating from it and some of the paper used to wrap the bottles had evidence of minor combustion.  The customer was contacted and could not tell us what was in the bag.  The customer and his mother (also traveling) could only tell us that the bag contained herbs and spiritual items which were packed by a third party who did not travel.  US CBP inspected the bag and found it also contained several bottles of liquid mercury.  The bag was placed under a post entry seal by US CBP pending an inspection by FAA and FDA.  The bag is currently in undeclared DG storage area in the ETD room.
